EDA is open-ended, and it is up to you to decide how to look at different ways to slice and dice your data. A good starting point is to look at the requirements for the FDA documentation in the final part of this project to guide (some) of the analyses you do.

This EDA should also help to inform you of how pneumonia looks in the wild. E.g. what other types of diseases it's commonly found with, how often it is found, what ages it affects, etc.

Note that this NIH dataset was not specifically acquired for pneumonia. So, while this is a representation of 'pneumonia in the wild,' the prevalence of pneumonia may be different if you were to take only chest x-rays that were acquired in an ER setting with suspicion of pneumonia.

Perform the following EDA:

  • The patient demographic data such as gender, age, patient position,etc. (as it is available)
  • The x-ray views taken (i.e. view position)
  • The number of cases including:
    • number of pneumonia cases,
    • number of non-pneumonia cases
  • The distribution of other diseases that are comorbid with pneumonia
  • Number of disease per patient
  • Pixel-level assessments of the imaging data for healthy & disease states of interest (e.g. histograms of intensity values) and compare distributions across diseases.

Note: use full NIH data to perform the first a few EDA items and use sample_labels.csv for the pixel-level assassements.

Also, describe your findings and how will you set up the model training based on the findings.

In [19]:
for label in findings:
    male_counts = all_xray_df[all_xray_df['Patient Gender']=='M'][label].sum()
    female_counts = all_xray_df[all_xray_df['Patient Gender']=='F'][label].sum()
    
    if male_counts < female_counts:
        print('%s: Predominately found in Females' % (label.upper()))
        
    elif male_counts > female_counts:
        print('%s: Predominately found in Males' % (label.upper()))
        
    else:
        print('%s: Equally found in both genders' % (label.upper()))

for label in labels:
    AP_view_pos = all_xray_df[all_xray_df['View Position']=='AP'][label].sum()
    PA_view_pos = all_xray_df[all_xray_df['View Position']=='PA'][label].sum()
    
    if AP_view_pos < PA_view_pos:
        print('%s: has more PA view compared to AP views.' % (label.upper()))
        
    elif AP_view_pos > PA_view_pos:
        print('%s: has fewer PA views compared to AP views.' % (label.upper()))
        
    else:
        print('%s: Equally found in both view positions.' % (label.upper()))

We see more than half of the patient population in the data are not diagnosed with any diseases (53.25% of the population) [i.e., identified with the No Findings tag]. Meanwhile, others seem to suffer from multiple (cooccurring) conditions like the case with 4 patients (0.01% of the population) having 13 conditions reported, and another case with 7 patients (0.02% of the population) having 12 conditions reported.

Since more than half of the population have reported 0 diseases, we believe it is necessary for us to drop some of the records for the purpose of creating a more reliable data set for training and validating any network architecture of choice.

for disease in sample_labels:
    
    print('Pixel-level assessments of {} cases:'.format(disease.upper()))
    
    # Current image path from dir.
    img_path = data_sample[data_sample["Finding Labels"]==disease].sample(5, random_state=RND_STATE)["path"]

    plt.figure(figsize=(30, 5))
    for i in range(len(img_path)):
        plt.subplot(1, len(img_path), i+1).set_title(disease.upper(), fontsize='xx-large')

        plt.hist(((var-np.mean(var))/np.std(var)).ravel(), bins=200, color='navy')
        # plt.xlim(-3, 3)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.savefig('./out/EDA_Pixel_level_Assessments_of_{}_Cases.png'.format(disease), dpi=300)
    plt.show()
